      <p>The "Common Pour" column is where the disconnect between perception and reality becomes clear. A single pint of a 9 percent IPA at a brewery contains the same alcohol as nearly 2.5 standard drinks. A generous glass of wine at a restaurant is more than 1.5 standard drinks. A Long Island Iced Tea, which typically contains vodka, rum, tequila, gin, and triple sec, can contain 3 to 4 standard drinks in a single glass. When someone says they had "just a couple of drinks," the actual alcohol consumption could easily be double or triple what that phrase implies.</p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>BAC Estimation by Weight and Drinks</h2>
      <p>Blood Alcohol Concentration (BAC) is the measurement used to determine the level of alcohol in your bloodstream, expressed as a percentage. In all 50 U.S. states, a BAC of 0.08 percent is the legal limit for driving. However, impairment begins well before that threshold. Research shows that reaction time, judgment, and coordination begin to decline at BAC levels as low as 0.02 to 0.03 percent.</p>
      <p>The following table provides rough BAC estimates for males based on body weight and number of standard drinks consumed within one hour. These are approximations based on the Widmark formula and assume an empty stomach. For females, BAC is generally 15 to 20 percent higher than the male estimates at the same weight and drink count due to differences in body water content and metabolism.</p>

